article.description:
Allen Iverson scored six of his 34 points in
overtime to lead the Philadelphia 76ers to a 101-99 victory over
the Los Angeles Clippers on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Iverson scores six of his game-high 34 points in OT
article.linkText: Iverson helps 76ers pull away from Clippers in OT
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia 76ers are winning the type of games they lost early last season.
Iverson

Allen Iverson scored six of his 34 points with an injured right thumb in overtime to lead the Sixers to a 101-99 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers on Wednesday night. Philadelphia, which opened last year with five straight losses, has won three in a row since losing its opener. The Clippers have dropped three of four. "We won three games we might have lost,'' Sixers coach Larry Brown said. "Any win we can scratch is a plus until we get some guys back.'' The Sixers played without starting forward Derrick Coleman, backup center Samuel Dalembert and key reserve Monty Williams -- all out with knee injuries. Los Angeles had a chance to win in the final seconds, but Elton Brand missed a short turnaround and Michael Olowokandi missed the tip-in. Iverson grabbed the rebound and sealed it with a free throw. Iverson hurt his thumb on the final play of regulation when he missed a runner that would've won it. Iverson will be re-evaluated on Thursday, but he left the First Union Center without a splint on the thumb. "I thought it was broke, but I would've known that by now,'' Iverson said. Todd MacCulloch had 15 points and eight rebounds. Aaron McKie added 12 points, eight rebounds and five assists for Philadelphia. Brand had 21 points and 19 rebounds, Olowokandi had 14 points and 13 rebounds, and Eric Piatkowski and Corey Maggette each added 18 points for the Clippers. "We had two great looks at the end and we didn't get it done,'' Clippers coach Alvin Gentry said. MacCulloch made one of two free throws to give the Sixers a 98-97 lead with 1:18 left in overtime. After Brand missed a short turnaround, Iverson hit a 19-footer to make it 100-97. Andre Miller cut it to 100-99 with two free throws, and the Clippers got the ball back when MacCulloch failed to catch a long pass from McKie. But Brand and Olowokandi missed their attempts. "We're just finding ways to win,'' McKie said. "We're not playing our best basketball. That's a good sign. Things will get better for us. We have a lot of new guys. We have to get used to each other.'' Iverson missed seven straight shots before he hit a 20-footer to give the Sixers a 96-95 lead midway through the extra period. After Olowokandi's short jumper put the Clippers ahead 97-96, Iverson made one of two free throws to tie it at 96 with 1:41 left. Brand made one of two free throws to tie it at 92 with 18.5 seconds left after Eric Snow gave the Sixers a one-point lead with a 15-footer. Iverson, who shot just 35 percent (28-for-80) in the first three games, was 9-for-18 at one point before finishing 11-for-28. Los Angeles committed 23 turnovers to Philadelphia's 8. "We've played long enough that we should win these type of games,'' Brand said. The Clippers, who trailed 47-43 at halftime, built their biggest lead, 74-62, following a 26-9 run. Maggette, who had 17 points in the third quarter after scoring none in the first half, scored seven of the last nine points during the spurt with a layup, a 3-pointer and two free throws. Philadelphia closed the second quarter with a 10-0 run to make it 47-43 at the half. Iverson's jumper with 1:05 left gave the Sixers their first lead since it was 6-4. Game notes
The Sixers have won three straight over the Clippers, their longest winning streak against them since winning seven in a row from 1988-1991. ... Iverson has reached double figures in scoring in 124 straight games, the longest streak in the NBA. ... Guard Quentin Richardson played 22 minutes and scored six points for the Clippers despite a hyperextended right knee. ... The Sixers had just one turnover in the first half. ... Sixers forward Keith Van Horn, playing with a sprained left ankle that he injured in practice Tuesday, was 3-for-10 for eight points and 11 rebounds before fouling out with 2:54 left in OT. ... Snow had 14 points and eight assists before fouling out with 3:10 left in OT. ... Miller had 13 points and 13 assists.
